    "discriminators": [
     "Mass sets the pitch. A church or tower bell is LOW (hum well under ~300 Hz), rings for many seconds, and carries the famous inharmonic partial set — roughly 2.0, 2.4, 3.0 and 4.2 times the hum, nowhere near integers. High inharmonicity plus a very long decay_time_seconds_60db plus a low f0 is one of the strongest single signatures in UCS.",
     "Every other bell is smaller, hence higher and shorter: BELLS-HANDBELL and especially BELLS-ANIMAL sit far up in pitch with a fraction of the ring time.",
     "BELLS-GONG rings just as long but is a disc, not a cast bell: much less pitched (low harmonicity) and its brightness RISES after the strike instead of decaying flat.",
     "Peals and tolling give a slow periodic onset train; a single toll is equally valid."
    ],
